Content:
In a problem I’m working on, I have positive integers $a,b,c,d$ satisfying $$
(ab)^2-2(cd)^2=1.  \tag{1}
$$ (So evidently $cd$ is a Pell number, and $ab$ is its companion.) Furthermore, say the following divisibility conditions also hold: \begin{align}
a &\mid (b^2+2c^2) \\
b &\mid (a^2-2d^2) \\ \tag{2}
c &\mid (a^2+d^2) \\
d &\mid (b^2-c^2).
\end{align} A brute-force computer search turns up only two solutions so far: $(a,b,c,d)=(3,1,1,2)$ and $(a,b,c,d)=(3,1,2,1)$ . I believe they may be the only ones. I’ve tried to algebraically prove that conjecture, to no avail. From the divisibility system, we see that $a$ must be of the form $x^2+2y^2$ , and $c$ must be of the form $u^2+v^2$ . From $(1),$ we deduce, for example, that $\gcd(ab,cd)=1$ , and also $ab=r^2+2s^2$ (so $b$ is also of that form) and $cd=2rs$ with $r^2-2s^2=\pm1$ . But I can’t seem to find the magic combination to complete the proof. Any hints, assistance, or references would be appreciated.
